    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Rev. S. Morais<lb/>
            Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>This little<lb/> offering &#40;which has been<lb/> worked by my own hands&#41;<lb/> is but a very small token<lb/> of the respect and regard<lb/> which the donor entertains<lb/> for yourself&#58; yet may<lb/> not hope that its usefulness<lb/> will compensate for the<lb/> insignificance of the gift&#44;<lb/> and that when placing<lb/> your pen between the<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>muslin folds&#44; these may<lb/> recall to your mind a<lb/> youthful but sincere<lb/> friend.<lb/>
            Wishing that every<lb/> happiness attendant upon<lb/> this joyful season may be<lb/> yours for many years to come&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>I am&#44; dear sir&#44;<lb/>
            With sentiments of esteem&#44;<lb/>
            Very sincerely yours&#44;<lb/>
            Mary M. Cohen<lb/></p>
            
            <p>1828 Rittenhouse Square.<lb/>
            Purim 5633.<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>My dear friend<lb/></p>
            <p>The work is as ingenious as it is useful&#44; but the thought which<lb/> directed the hand is lovely.  &#34;I thank you&#34; sounds so cold and formal&#44;<lb/> that I will not say it.  But this acknowledgment I will make<lb/> in all sincerity.  Among the few&#44; upon whom I look with feelings<lb/> akin to parental affection your dear self stands foremost.  Hence&#44;<lb/> any token of friendship&#44; evincing a reciprocation of sentiments&#44; occasions<lb/> a gratification more deeply experienced than adequately expressed.<lb/>  That this virtual regard may never alter&#44; and that you may live<lb/> long and happy amidst your beautiful surroundings is the wish of<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours very truly<lb/>
            S. Morais<lb/>
            Purim 5633.<lb/></p>

        </body>
    </text>
